    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-03-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-03-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="52"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conference 184.00101/25</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minutes of the Meetings of the American Commissioners
                        Plenipotentiary, March 1, 1919</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1919-03-01">March 1, 1919</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Present</hi>: Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LR1"
                            >Lansing</persName>, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WH1">White</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BGTH1">General Bliss</persName>, Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_WW1">H. R. Wilson</persName>.</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="center">11</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName> introduced Memorandum No
                        121<note n="64" xml:id="d52fn64">Not printed.</note> concerning Prof. Herron
                    and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WH1">White</persName>.<note n="65"
                        xml:id="d52fn65">
                        <persName>George D. Herron</persName> and <persName>William Allen
                            White</persName> had been selected to represent the United States at the
                        Prinkipo Conference.</note> The Commissioners decided that Prof Herron and
                    Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WH1">White</persName> should not remain attached to
                    the Commission in view of the present situation concerning Prinkipo, nor should
                    they proceed with the organization of their delegation.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
